# Frontend: feature module structure

Each feature is a folder at `frontend/app/features/<name>/` with three layers.

## models/<name>.ts

```typescript
type MyModelRaw = DeepPartial<MyModel>

export interface MyModel {
  id: string | null
  organization_id: string | null
  created_at: string | null
  updated_at: string | null
  name: string
}

export const myModelCodec = createCodec<MyModel>({
  decode: (raw: MyModelRaw) => ({
    id: raw.id || null,
    organization_id: raw.organization_id || null,
    created_at: raw.created_at || null,
    updated_at: raw.updated_at || null,
    name: raw.name ?? '',
  }),
  encode: (data) => ({
    organization_id: data.organization_id || null,
    name: data.name || null,
  }),
})
```

- `id` is `string | null` (UUID from backend)
- `decode` — API response → typed object (all fields with defaults)
- `encode` — typed object → API payload (only writable fields, no `id`/`created_at`/`updated_at`)
- `createCodec`, `DeepPartial`, `AppModel` are auto-imported from `shared/toolkits/repo/`

## repos/<name>Repo.ts

```typescript
import { myModelCodec } from '../models/myModel'

export const useMyModelRepo = defineStore('myModelRepo', () => {
  const config = getRepoConfig({ resource: 'my-models', codec: myModelCodec })
  const { state, actions } = createAppRepo(config)()
  return { ...state, ...actions }
})
```

- `resource` — matches the backend URL prefix (kebab-case, plural)
- `defineStore`, `getRepoConfig`, `createAppRepo` are auto-imported
- Register the repo in `app/shared/composables/useRepo.ts`, then use `useRepo('myModel')` in views

## UI building blocks

Templates are built on shared primitives from `shared/ui/app/` and `shared/ui/template/`:

| Component | Role |
|---|---|
| `AppSection` | Page/section wrapper with `title`, `description`, optional `backAction` |
| `AppList` | Table or list with built-in search (`showSearch`) and pagination |
| `AppListTemplate` | `AppSection` + `AppList` + optional create button + modal detail |
| `AppDetailTemplate` | `AppSection` + detail form with save/delete actions |
| `AppModal` | Dialog wrapper with optional `title` / `subtitle` |
| `AppColumn` | DataTable column with optional `format` callback |
| `AppSelect` | Select backed by a repo (`:repo="useRepo('user')"`) |
| `AppTemplateActions` | Row of action buttons with per-action loading and optional toasts |

`AppTemplateActions` accepts `actions: AppTemplateAction[]` (label, icon, `action`, notifications, `hidden`, `mode`). Used inside `AppDetailActions`; can be placed in `#actions` slots for custom toolbars.

`AppSection` uses `description` for the subtitle text under the title (not `subtitle`).

`templateVariant`: `page` (default), `section`, `flat-section` — controls title size and block styling.

## AppListTemplate — universal list component

`AppListTemplate` is the standard way to display any list: in a page view, inside a detail page section, or nested inside a modal. Columns via PrimeVue `Column` or `AppColumn` (for `format`).

### Navigation mode (page list view)

Used in `views/MyModelListView.vue` — clicking a row navigates to the detail page.

```vue
<template>
  <AppListTemplate
    title="My Models"
    description="Manage models"
    detail-route-name="settings-my-models-id"
    :repo="useRepo('myModel')"
    filter
  >
    <Column field="name" header="Name" />
  </AppListTemplate>
</template>
```

### Modal mode (section component or nested list)

Used when a list belongs to a parent entity. The edit form opens in `AppModal` via embedded `AppDetailTemplate` and the `#detail-modal` slot.

```vue
<template>
  <AppListTemplate
    title="My Models"
    detail-mode="modal"
    template-variant="section"
    :extra-params="{ parent_id: props.parentId }"
    :build-new-item="() => myModelCodec.decode({ parent_id: props.parentId })"
    :repo="useRepo('myModel')"
  >
    <AppColumn header="Name" :format="(row) => row.name || '—'" />

    <template #detail-modal="{ detailItem }">
      <AppInput v-model="detailItem.name" label="Name" />

      <MyNestedSection v-if="detailItem.id" :parent-id="detailItem.id" />
    </template>
  </AppListTemplate>
</template>

<script setup lang="ts">
import { myModelCodec } from '../models/myModel'

const props = defineProps<{ parentId: string }>()
</script>
```

Key props:

| Prop | Description |
|---|---|
| `detail-route-name` | Route name to navigate to on row click (navigation mode, `detail-mode="route"`) |
| `detail-mode="modal"` | Open detail in a modal instead of navigating |
| `:extra-params` | Extra query params (e.g. filter by parent id) |
| `:build-new-item` | Factory for a new item (pre-filled with parent reference) |
| `filter` | Enable server-side search (sends `search` query param) |
| `show-search` | Show/hide search input (default `true`) |

## views/MyModelDetailView.vue

```vue
<template>
  <AppDetailTemplate
    :build-new-item="() => myModelCodec.decode({ organization_id: organizationId })"
    title="My Model"
    :repo="useRepo('myModel')"
    :back-action="() => navigateTo({ name: 'settings-my-models' })"
  >
    <template #default="{ item, isCreating }">
      <AppInput v-model="item.name" label="Name" />
    </template>
  </AppDetailTemplate>
</template>

<script setup lang="ts">
import { myModelCodec } from '../models/myModel'

const { organizationId } = useOrganization()
</script>
```

`AppDetailTemplate` props worth knowing:

| Prop | Description |
|---|---|
| `mode` | `page` (load from route param) or `inline` (item passed via `:item`) |
| `:back-action` | Custom back navigation; defaults to `router.back()` in page mode |
| `:actions-props` | Hide or customize save/delete/cancel actions |
| `hide-back-button` | Hide back button (used inside modals) |

## Wiring up

**Pages** — create `app/pages/settings/my-models/index.vue` and `[id].vue`:
```vue
<template><MyModelListView /></template>
<script setup lang="ts">
import MyModelListView from '~/features/my-model/views/MyModelListView.vue'
</script>
```

**Layout** (`app/layouts/settings.vue`) — add to `navigationSections`:
```typescript
{ to: { name: 'settings-my-models' }, label: 'My Models', icon: 'lucide:box' }
```

**Repo registry** — add to `app/shared/composables/useRepo.ts`:
```typescript
myModel: useMyModelRepo,
```

## Labels — feature composables

Prefer a feature composable (for example `composables/useMyModelLabels.ts`) with `LabelConfig` maps and `getXxx()` helpers instead of ad hoc `Record<string, string>` maps in components.

## Async actions — `useActionState`

Use `useActionState` from `~/shared/composables/useActionState` for button handlers, modal flows, and other async work that should show loading state and optional toasts. Wire `:loading` to `someState.loading.value` and `@click` to `someState.execute`.

```typescript
const handleSaveState = useActionState(
  async () => {
    if (!props.entity.id) return
    await repo.update(props.entity.id, payload.value)
    model.value = false
  },
  {
    successNotification: 'Saved successfully',
    errorNotification: 'Failed to save',
  },
)
```

- Pass `successNotification` / `errorNotification` when user feedback is required; omit both for silent loads.
- Do not duplicate manual `ref` loading flags and `try/finally` around the same operation when `useActionState` already manages `loading`.

## Rules

- Nuxt route names are derived from the file path: `settings/my-models/[id].vue` → `settings-my-models-id`
- `useOrganization()` is auto-imported and provides `organizationId` for the current org
- `$api` is a pre-configured fetch client with `baseURL: /api/v1` and `Organization-Key` header
- Never use `useFetch` directly — always go through a repo
- Prefer `useRepo('key')` in views over importing repo stores directly
- Use `AppColumn` / `AppSelect` 
